status_message:
Donald Trump's hand gestures are his second language. We try to decode some of his most-used movements. 

"The Pointer"  — also called "School Marming" by behavioral scientists — tells people to listen up. 

"The Denier" is a classic gesture for denial and disapproval. 

"The Highlighter" is one of Trump's signature gestures. According to behavioral consultant Vanessa Van Edwards, the motion "indicates that he wants to drill down into a point that you should remember, it's as if he is 'hand picking' it for you." 

"The Delayer" is a tactic Trump uses while thinking of his next point. 

"The Includer," Van Edwards explains that it's a combination of the "God pose" and a shrug. It's as if he's saying, "Why wouldn't you want to vote for me?"
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
Thousands head to National Mall to commemorate March on Washington's 50th anniversary. 

The gathering Saturday came under crystal-clear skies that set a new summer standard for perfection, even as the rhetoric about the pursuit of freedom soared to near a standard of perfection set 50 years before.

It was a day when people spoke of the future of race in America and of one man's vision, so forcefully delivered that five decades later the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s "I Have a Dream" speech ranks with Abraham Lincoln's Gettysburg Address and Franklin D. Roosevelt's "Day of Infamy" speech to Congress as the most iconic in U.S. history.

"Daddy is smiling up above, knowing that by your presence you will keep his dream alive," Martin Luther King III said from the top step of the Lincoln Memorial, where his father's memorable speech capped the historic 1963 March on Washington.

MORE PHOTOS: http://wapo.st/158gNqI
link_name: Timeline Photos

Former British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has died after suffering a stroke. She was 87. http://wapo.st/Y810io 

She transformed Britain and transfixed America during the 1980s,  serving 11 1/2 uninterrupted years in office before stepping down Nov. 28, 1990. 

Thatcher set out to dismantle Britain's cradle-to-grave welfare state by selling off scores of massive state-owned industries, crushing the power of organized labor and cutting government spending with the purpose of liberating the nation from what she called a "culture of dependency."

UPDATE: The majority of Supreme Court justices seemed skeptical of the Defense of Marriage Act. http://wapo.st/13xxhHh

The Justices asked if DOMA created unequal classes of married couples by extending federal benefits only to marriages between a man and a woman. 

Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, thought likely to be the deciding vote, told the lawyer  defending DOMA that it did not promote "uniformity" in federal law.

Edith Windsor, the plaintiff who had to pay more than $300,000 in taxes after her wife's death, said oral arguments "went beautifully." http://wapo.st/XH9MUn

status_message:
Today the U.S. Supreme Court will hear oral arguments in a challenge to the 1996 Defense of Marriage Act. 

DOMA denies federal benefits to same-sex couples who are legally married in the states where they live while offering the same benefits to opposite-sex married couples. 

House Republicans John Boehener, Eric Cantor and Kevin McCarthy are defending DOMA because Obama's solicitor general and House Democrats have refused to defend it. The group has hired George W. Bush's former solicitor general to make the case that it is constitutional to deny married same-sex couples federal benefits. 

Read more about the specifics of the case that could change the course of same-sex marriage in America. http://wapo.st/11LYzJ0

Lawyers have concluded their oral arguments in one of the same-sex marriage cases before the Supreme Court.

Washington lawyer Charles J. Cooper defended Prop 8, a California measure that defines marriage as between a man and a woman, by arguing that procreation is a vital state interest. Cooper said that since same-sex couples cannot have their own children, their marriages do not address this interest. 

Justice Kagan asked whether, if procreation were such a vital interest, marriage licences should not be issued to heterosexual couples over 55.

Meet Bill and Shelley. This is their first Valentine's Day as a married couple. Their story is worth sharing. http://wapo.st/VLyF5x 

--------------

TRUE LOVE | Bill Ott will always remember the moment he met Shelley Belgard. It was in spring 1988. He was 12 and sometimes shy. Into music, sports and, suddenly, girls.

Shelley was three years older, chatty and outgoing. They'd both shown up at a Montgomery County social club looking for friends, fun and the kind of acceptance that seems so elusive during teen life.

Shelley smiled. Bill introduced himself. And that was it. "I didn't know what love was," he says. "Until I met her."

He was sure it was the real thing, but nobody ever believes that coming from a 12-year-old.

Certainly not one with Down syndrome.

Continue reading Bill and Shelley's story: http://wapo.st/VLyF5x

How Obama became black

He was too dark in Indonesia. A hapa child — half and half — in Hawaii. Multicultural in Los Angeles. An "Invisible Man" in New York. And finally, Barack Obama was black on the South Side of Chicago. This journey of racial self-discovery and reinvention is chronicled in David Maraniss's biography, "Barack Obama: The Story."
